            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "The scent of cardamom and the pressure of expectation defined Aaron Sharma's childhood in Fremont. The only son of Indian immigrants, his parents envisioned a straightforward path for him paved with a STEM degree from Berkeley and a lucrative career in Silicon Valley. Aaron, however, was always more interested in people than in code. He\u2019d spend hours listening to the stories of his neighbors, fascinated by the intricate web of culture, class, and opportunity that shaped their lives.\n\nHe enrolled at San Francisco State University, choosing Sociology as a major, a decision that caused quiet friction at the family dinner table. He loved the city, the way a dozen languages could be heard on a single block of the Mission, and felt he\u2019d finally found his place. The turning point came during his junior year when his mother suffered a serious health crisis. Aaron put his studies on hold to help his family navigate confusing hospital bureaucracies and saw firsthand the gaps in care for non-English speakers. The abstract theories from his textbooks became stark reality.\n\nHe never returned to finish his degree. Instead, ignited by a new sense of purpose, he began volunteering at a community health clinic. His empathy and natural ability to connect with people from all walks of life quickly earned him a paid position. Now, as a Community Outreach Coordinator, he\u2019s the bridge between underserved populations and the resources they desperately need, working on everything from public health campaigns to after-school program enrollment.\n\nAaron lives in a crowded but friendly Inner Richmond apartment with two old college friends. His day begins with the familiar rumble of the 38 Geary bus, a 4.5-mile commute he uses to catch up on podcasts about urban policy. Evenings are often spent cooking with his roommates or decompressing with a run through Golden Gate Park. His social life is deeply intertwined with his work and his neighborhood.\n\nHis dreams are practical, not grandiose. He hopes to eventually move into a policy-making role within the city\u2019s health department, to affect systemic change rather than just addressing its symptoms. More immediately, he dreams of affording a one-bedroom apartment. For Aaron, San Francisco isn\u2019t the glittering world of tech startups; it\u2019s the resilient, complex, and often struggling community he serves every day, and he remains devoted to mending its social fabric, one person at a time."
