            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the fluorescent hum of the hospital waiting room. His mother, small in the starched bed, asked a question in Hindi, her voice trembling. The nurse sighed, a sound of pure impatience. Aaron stepped forward, translating his mother\u2019s fear and the nurse\u2019s clipped response. In that cold, clinical gap between languages, his abstract sociological studies collapsed into a single, burning purpose. He wasn't just his mother's son; he was her advocate. This occurred during his junior year at SF State.\n\n2.\nThe scent of his mother's chai filled the air, thick with unspoken expectation. His father had been talking about internships at Google. Aaron took a breath, the words feeling heavy in his mouth. \"I'm majoring in Sociology.\" The silence that followed was heavier than any argument. It wasn\u2019t anger, but a deep, quiet disappointment that hurt more. Occurring during his freshman year, it was the moment he chose his own uncertain path over their secure one, an act that defined his independence.\n\n3.\nHe recalls Mrs. Chan, who had been living in a world of muffled sound for years. He spent two weeks navigating a maze of paperwork for her hearing aids. The day they finally worked, she called her granddaughter. Aaron watched as Mrs. Chan\u2019s eyes widened, filling with tears as she heard the child\u2019s voice clearly for the first time. That quiet joy, experienced early in his volunteering career, was more validating than any diploma would have been. It was proof his work mattered.\n\n4.\nIt was a Tuesday evening his freshman year, walking down 24th Street in the Mission. The smell of pupusas from one doorway mixed with roasting coffee from another. On the corner, a group of friends laughed in Spanish, while down the block, a family haggled over produce in Cantonese. He felt the city\u2019s rhythm\u2014a vibrant, chaotic symphony so different from Fremont. In that moment, he knew he had found his place, feeling his own story finally clicking into the city's complex narrative.\n\n5.\nLast winter, crammed onto the 38 Geary, he was listening to a podcast on municipal housing policy. He glanced over and saw the elderly man beside him squinting at an eviction notice, the dense legal text a stark white in his weathered hands. Aaron muted the theorist in his earbuds. The chasm between the academic discussion of the problem and the quiet panic on the man\u2019s face was immense. It was a humbling, recent reminder to never lose sight of the person behind the policy."
